                <head>48. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At the 311th meeting of the National Security Council on January 31, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> made the following remarks
                    concerning the situation in Egypt during his review of significant world
                    developments affecting United States security:</p>
                <p>“In Egypt, said Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName>, internal
                    pressures against <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName> were
                    rising—especially economic pressures. There had also been reports of bickering m
                    the Revolutionary Council and rumors of plots to destroy <persName
                        corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName> thought that none of these plots was likely to succeed at
                    this time. He then provided the Council with an analysis of the status of
                        <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>’s external position
                    vis-à-vis the various countries of the Middle East. The majority of the
                    governments in the area are opposed to <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName> or are lukewarm. The people, on the other hand, are
                    sympathetic.” (Memorandum of discussion; Eisenhower Library, Whitman File,
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
            </div>
